<dl id="n54119m"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54119m">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54119m"> 119(m)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> The River, - salt, brine, <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54119m"><li>FW 110.01f </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/lexe.htm#n54119m">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/l39e.htm#n54119m">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54119m">MS BL 47476a-209</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:441 <a name="ed11" href="../../ff/fdra/eda.htm#ed11">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/e/ed11.htm#n54119m">Draft: I.5&sect;1.11</a>/4.11</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>The river</mark> people were landsmen and had the landsmen&apos;s terror of the ocean. They were not even boatmen for very little of their shallow river was navigible. While the desire for a more plentiful supply of that supreme luxury&mdash;<mark>salt</mark>&mdash;drove them to the sea shores, the watery waste remained for a long time a place of mystery and terror&mdash;a symbol of oblivion. The fact that the <mark>brine-laden</mark> water, easily evaporated by the sun on the flat mud shores, gave them this wonderful salt, which river water could not provide, probably added to the mystery, if not to the terror. <small> Carl Crow, <a name="CCMK" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CCMK"><cite title="source">Master Kung. The Story of Confucius</cite></a> (Sep 1937) 37</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
